Casablanca,t2jBSAWCg5s,UgwrEXCnBfUuus01vk14AaABAg,,@steelers6titles,"Note that Renault is a double-crosser until the end; he phones Strasser instead of the airport, to warn him of the impending escape.  He has a history of corruption,  which includes bribery and offering escape for sex.  Rick, despite his professed cynicism, in reality hates dishonesty and corruption.  Yet he seemingly trusts Renault at the end, which, given the latter's history, is somewhat mystifying.  Rick is no fool.  But the ending fits the film.  We'll never know if the partnership succeeded.",2026-05-02T17:12:38Z,2026-05-02T17:13:50Z,0,False,0.0,2026-05-03T02:00:56.807428
Casablanca,t2jBSAWCg5s,UgxKHjVI_bx-YorQJLJ4AaABAg,,@steelers6titles,"Polish immigrants Harry, Sam, and Albert Warner, along with youngest brother Jack,  got a projector and opened a theater, the Cascade, in New Castle, Pennsylvania, in 1906.  The building is preserved as a museum.  The Canadian-born youngest brother, Jack L. Warner, ran the studio they later founded; his name is on the films it produced.",2026-05-02T16:57:52Z,2026-05-02T17:08:58Z,0,False,0.0,2026-05-03T02:00:56.807431
