Casablanca,t2jBSAWCg5s,Ugy3IvaKbqWZx68EYZ14AaABAg,,@samuellord8576,"Nice reaction!  However, you are mistaken in thinking that Rick has undergone character development.  He had fought for several years against fascists for very little payment.  Recall, he _claims_ he was well paid, but that supports his neutral, self-serving legend.  Of course he was a patriot…he fought for civilization itself.

And recall how he was on the Germans’ blacklist for many years.  And finally, he doesn’t return to America.  Reasons are murky, implying criminality.  

These multiple facets of his legend mean only one thing: Rick is an American agent, working for free, well placed to gather information about Nazi activities in French Africa.  His supposed criminal past in America was a carefully constructed tissue of lies.  And this is how the great Victor Lazlo came to serve the Allies.

On the other hand, he did push Ilsa to part with Victor, but she refused.  So the standard storyline is given for most audiences.  But the implication is strong that the story had two conflicting narratives. that he was an asset, that he wasn’t.  We can choose either, as we wish!",2026-05-02T09:04:11Z,2026-05-02T09:05:56Z,0,False,0.0,2026-05-03T02:00:56.807478
