Casablanca,t2jBSAWCg5s,UgziG7csS_jsFOzFtZN4AaABAg,,@ammaleslie509,"Watching you watch this movie through such innocent eyes was very sweet.  Thank you.

If (when!) you watch this movie again in the future, some of the confusing parts will be clearer to you.

But the movie is so good that you get swept up in it even though some of the important details went past you.

And you figured out that Ilsa thought her husband was dead WAY faster than most people, so you get a gold star for that!

Big things you missed (that you may appreciate on future viewings):

* The Nazis were upset when the people in the cafe drowned out the German drinking song with the French National anthem, because it meant the local people still patriotically thought of themselves as French (or whatever country they were from, they identified more with the French than the Nazis) and had not fully surrendered in their hearts to the occupying forces from Germany--it was a moment of defiance.  If Laszlo could create that atmosphere of resistance among strangers in a bar, they worried that he could influence rebellion in the general population the longer he stayed in Casablanca.  This movie is a love story on many levels--including love of COUNTRY.

* Captain Renault was exploiting desperate young women by offering them exit visas in exchange for sex.  The girl who had only been married was planning to have sex with Renault in exchange for exit visas, and she was asking Rick two questions:  (1) if I sleep with Renault, will he keep his word and give us the visas? and 2) If a woman did ""a bad thing"" for your freedom because she loved you, would you be able to forgive her?  Rick says ""no one ever loved me like that"" and he is thinking about his own heartbreak, but then he feels moved to help the husband win at the roulette wheel so she won't have to give herself to Renault.

* The date on the check Rick is signing when we first meet him shows that it is before Pearl Harbor, before the U.S. entered the war.  (That date would have been immediately obvious to every person in the US watching the film then.)  Watching it now decades after we know the Nazis lost is VERY different than people felt watching it in theatres in 1942 when the United States had JUST entered the war but NO ONE KNEW WHICH SIDE WAS GOING TO WIN.  This movie created a sense of optimism about the war effort--a sense that the rebellion would succeed and the Nazis would fail because the people of honor and integrity were all on the side of the Allies. The ""Bulgarian"" girl played by actress Joy Page, Dooley Wilson (the piano player) and Humphrey Bogart are the only three actors with speaking parts who were born in the United States.  So the international cast, in a subliminal way,, helped create the hopeful notion that the whole world was united against the Nazis and therefore it was more likely the Allies would win.  Again--a love story that is also about love of country.

Whole shelves full of books have been written about this movie so I've said enough.  The more you watch Casablanca the more you will appreciate it.",2026-05-02T04:04:05Z,2026-05-02T04:34:50Z,0,False,0.0,2026-05-03T02:00:56.807575
