Casablanca,t2jBSAWCg5s,UgxzMcjxhVAC6TjIId94AaABAg,,@geraldclough1099,"In 1942, 15,000 French francs (known later as ""old francs"") would have been roughly 300 U.S. dollars of that time. Roughly $6,000 in today's U.S. dollar. No small amount, especially when cash was hard to come by. 15,000 francs was about the high end of what the French unions wanted a worker to be paid per month. All this is rough. The French franc was understandable unstable. But it gives you an idea of how much was involved.

A common error is thinking that Ugarte said the letters were signed by General de Gaulle. Not so. de Gaulle was in exile in England trying to organize the Free French forces and being a nuisance to the British. He actually says the letters are signed by General Weygand. Maxime Weygand was the Vichy government commander for North Africa. The two names sound much the same. The original script has the name correct. But it is often mistakenly subtitled as de Gaulle. Showing anything signed by de Gaulle would just get you shot.  Many of the actors and extras were actual refugees and other displaced persons and would have known better. The actor playing the German officer only agreed to do it on the condition that the German would be a villain.",2026-05-02T02:59:30Z,2026-05-02T03:08:00Z,0,False,0.0,2026-05-03T02:00:56.807626
Casablanca,t2jBSAWCg5s,UgxgEfQNZJLMGKsHSAx4AaABAg,,@jnagarya519,"The ""beautiful friendship"" line -- the US began its involvement in the European theater of the war by invading at French Morocco.  It represents the alliance between the US and France.",2026-05-02T02:54:47Z,2026-05-02T02:54:47Z,0,False,0.0,2026-05-03T02:00:56.807629
