Casablanca,MF7JH_54d8c,UgxNIhZd6nvm6F531Kh4AaABAg,,@Just_another_Euro_dude,"Old classic movies are still fantastic as any from the current age. Maybe few tiny details change throughout the decades, maybe a bit of mentality changes, and a LOT of technology changes, but the ESSENCE of the quality REMAINS, regardless if it's 1920s, 30s, 40s ,50s, 60s ,70s, 80s, 90s, 00s, 10s or 20s (again 😅)...
Few years ago i was naive enough to believe that old black and white movies are somehow inferior to the more modern ones, let's say starting from the 1980s and forward. But then i started watching a lot of the classics from the golden age of Hollywood and from the European cinema and from the Japanese cinema and boy i was so wrong. Watched the Bicycle thieves, watched the Seven Samurai, watched the White Heat with James Cagney, and Public Enemy, and also Scarface with Paul Muni. The method of the acting might be somewhat strange in those early 1930s movies i admit, (the infamous overacting) Public Enemy and The Scarface, but boy the classics from the 1940s and 1950s are just perfect. What Kurosawa did with The Seven samurai in 1954 was just an incredible achievement,  (almost a PERFECTION of a movie) and the emotion and warmth of the Italian Bicycle thieves from the 1948 is just something i didn't find in ANY movie of those times. It's amazing really. Classic is a classic regardless of the year but you need a bit of the life experience to realise that. It was impossible for me to realise that in my 20s or even in most of my 30s. I was the modern movies elitist. And was so soooo wrong. 😂 While interestingly enough i loved watching the old movies as a kid. Now in my early 40s i can't get enough of the old classics while STILL loving the modern cinema.",2025-03-14T07:21:59Z,2025-03-14T07:21:59Z,1,False,0.0,2026-05-03T02:01:12.683867
