AFCON,MU-oq7Nthp8,UgyxW3pVM1PQ9kQNaJ94AaABAg,,@parisluxe4192,"The decision must be made the moment Senegal leaves the field and the final whistle blows. From the moment the referee restarts the match, his decision is irrevocable. The Moroccans were surprised but lucid enough to want to restart the match at all costs? No, Morocco didn't want to stop the match because they had just been awarded a penalty and thought they were going to score it; we all know how that turned out. So you agree to restart the match, but you lose it and you file a complaint? If Brahim Diaz had scored the penalty, would you have filed a complaint? Well done, Morocco, you won by email and notifications, congratulations! We'll send you the cup and the trophies by email and notifications in six months.

I've been waiting since there's never been a case like this before. Ask Morocco how they won their first AFCON in 1976? During the final in Ethiopia against Guinea, to protest Cherif Souleyman's Guinean goal, the Moroccans left the field for over 30 minutes—yes, you read that right, 30 minutes—before returning and winning their first title (1-1, Morocco winning on goal difference). So, the rules must prevail and be respected, and Guinea is going to appeal to CAF, 50 years later, to reclaim its Cup? Seriously, were Regulations 82 and 83 written on the evening of January 18, 2026? They don't apply to Morocco in 1976? Isn't there a message that needs to be sent to the towelmen and ball boys? But wait, there's no corruption involved!!!",2026-03-19T16:10:13Z,2026-03-19T16:10:13Z,0,False,0.0,2026-05-03T02:02:33.964080
