Tourisme,RytpAWQMJPk,UgwgeW9EemTGPoMhGZt4AaABAg,,@DragonToothlessTwitch,"As a Tri-citizen living in Japan (Canada by birth (Hometown: Ottawa), US by naturalization, and British by descent), I only use passports from Canada and UK. While the Canadian passport has an extra burden regarding the passport photo certification (which is a major pain in Japan as most photographers don't have a stamp to apply to the back of the photo), it still beats the feeling of being associated with the way the US has gone way to the fascism right-side of the political spectrum (social media having helped keep Americans in a smaller and smaller bubble of false reality).

I do share things about my adult years in the US before moving to Japan, but my students only care about learning of my life in Canada growing up (I moved to the US when I was 18 due to my dad's work). They like learning about my black bear encounters, tapping maple trees for sap which would become maple syrup, seeing Ottawa's Winterlude which is similar to the local Sapporo Snow Festival, and they like that unlike the American ALTs they've had in the past (who just want to go do their own thing at the end of the day and not interact with students), I'm willing to spend time helping students clean the classrooms. Many of those students have expressed interest in visiting Canada instead of the US, or even doing semesters in Canadian universities and thus avoiding the US altogether, because of my civility and genuine respect.",2026-04-29T09:27:22Z,2026-04-29T09:28:17Z,0,False,0.0,2026-05-03T02:03:04.699265
