Tourisme,tQG5jBBGn2Q,UgzcEytVKS2EAK7FqIl4AaABAg,,@antog42,"Thank you for a fantastic video. There's so much more and there were some very one-sided aspects to the video BUT your reaction and comments throughout are the key take away for me. Very few people living in South Africa understand the stress and fear they live under EVERY moment of their lives. One thing you didn't cover too much is that, despite living in a prison designed to keep them safe, crime in those suburbs and so-called 'safe-zones' is still rampant. Horrendous stuff still happens despite the 9 foot walls and electric fencing and motion detectors and panic buttons and armed response units. 

I was one of those who pushed the limits of what most white South Africans would call 'safe' both at work and play. But it was always done with a sense of fear and respect and I definitely never relaxed. I never wore jewelry or watches, I carried a cheap cellphone and tried not to travel with any electronic goods or camera equipment. 

I rode a popular walking/MTB trail to and from work everyday because I didn't trust drivers enough to use the roads. I assessed the route for choke points or danger areas where men could hide and wait. ! changed the times I rode, took different routes where possible and rode fast, especially through the danger areas I had identified. I made sure someone knew when I left and the route I took and I tried not carry anything with me. All of this was because it was HIGHLY likely that I would be robbed at some point, as that happended regularly. As you say, THIS IS NOT NORMAL!

I worked in Braamfontein / Hillbrow (Johannesburg) for the last 2 years before I left South Africa. My job involved walking around the streets, visiting a portfolio of buildings and I dealt with some very interesting characters. I loved it in the city dealing with so many diverse and vibrant people, cultures and situations and I tried to connect with as many people as I could. But I knew I was on borrowed time and something bad was going to happen. This was confirmed when a bar owner came to me and completely casually mentioned that if I wasn't me, I would be dead! I tried to keep calm and ask what he meant and he said that they know I am a good guy and because of that I wasn't dead (because of the job). 

That is how cheap life in SA is and how easily it can be ended. It is not normal to live like that.

PS. The portfolio of buildings I was involved with included one building that not even the police would go to. The building had been hijacked and any attempt to go there would be met with gunfire. The building is in central Johannesburg.",2026-05-02T12:18:09Z,2026-05-02T12:18:09Z,0,False,0.0,2026-05-03T02:03:05.778328
