CAN,lpsKNd8tqHI,Ugx74YAdMXrJeBaAB2B4AaABAg,,@yahdahjames6462,"The Bible itself does not claim to be the Word of God.   
The Bible clearly says that Jesus Christ is the 'Word'.  Period!
(John 1:14  And the “Word” was made flesh, and dwelt among us,)

Therefore . . . Jesus Christ himself is the 'WORD OF GOD'.  The Bible is simply a narrative written by men describing His life on earth as the Son of Man and as the Son of God.  
So yes . . . the words He spoke while on earth (red letters) can be considered 'The Word of God'.
 
Many people point to  2 Timothy 3:16-17  The verse stating ""All Scripture is God-breathed"" or inspired by God.  The problem is . . . most of the New Testament DID NOT EVEN EXIST when 2nd Timothy was written in the 60's AD!   First of all, none of the gospels including the books of Matthew, Mark, Luke, John, Peter, James, 1-2-3 John, Jude, or Revelation . . . all of which were written perhaps ten to forty years AFTER all of Apostle Paul's epistles.  So, what 'scriptures' was Paul talking about being 'inspired' if the rest of the New Testament had not been written yet?  
 
Nonetheless, that particular verse could NOT have been considered within the context of all the 'God-breathed scripture' being referred to . . . that actually DID EXIST at that time!

Secondly, the vast majority of critical Bible scholars do not believe that Paul even wrote 2nd Timothy in the first place. So, that scripture loses all credibility.
WHY?     
Vocabulary: If you compare the vocabulary between some of Paul’s undisputed letters, like Romans, the type of words used by the writer vary dramatically from the type of words used in 2nd Timothy.
AND . . .
Content: 
If you compare the theological content in 2 Timothy with what you find in an earlier letter, like 1 Thessalonians, the themes are very different. In 1 Thessalonians, Paul writes a lot about the second coming of Jesus, urging his readers to be prepared for His coming at any minute. 

However, in 2 Timothy, Paul is more concerned about training leaders for the next generation, as Paul knows that he is about to die soon, and he will not be around for much longer! In 2 Timothy 2:1-2, he urges Timothy to find others Timothy can teach, so that they in turn can teach others.

(There is a common list of “disputed” epistles where the authorship of Paul is in doubt including: 
Colossians, Ephesians, 2nd Thessalonians, 1 Timothy, 2 Timothy, and Titus)",2026-04-25T02:17:51Z,2026-04-25T02:38:19Z,0,False,0.0,2026-05-03T02:03:35.642714
